Thread Communication
Why Thread Communication?

When multiple threads depend on each other, continuously checking a condition (busy waiting/polling) wastes CPU.

Example:

Producer creates data.
Consumer needs that data.
Instead of checking repeatedly, the consumer waits and the producer notifies when the data is ready.

Purpose: Efficient coordination between threads without wasting CPU.

    wait()
    Puts the current thread into the WAITING state.
    Releases the object's monitor lock so other threads can enter the synchronized block.
    The thread remains waiting until another thread calls notify() or notifyAll().
    Must be called inside a synchronized block/method.
    notify()
    Wakes up one waiting thread (chosen by the JVM).
    Does NOT release the lock immediately.
    The awakened thread can continue only after the current thread exits the synchronized block and releases the lock.
    notifyAll()
    Wakes up all waiting threads.
    All awakened threads compete for the same lock.
    Only one thread acquires the lock first; others wait again until the lock becomes available.